## Level 18 → Level 19
**Objective:** Read the `readme` file in the home directory of bandit18
but `.bashrc` has been modified to automatically log you out the moment
you log in — printing "Byebye!" and terminating the session immediately.

**Commands Used:**
```bash
ssh bandit18@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220 "cat ~/readme"
# logs in, runs cat ~/readme, prints output, exits — all in one step
```

**What is `.bashrc`?**
- A hidden configuration file in every Linux user's home directory
- Automatically executed every time a new interactive shell session starts
- Normally used for setting aliases, environment variables, and
  custom configurations
- In this level it was modified to run an exit command on login —
  a simple but effective way to lock someone out
- This is a real technique used by attackers to maintain persistence
  or lock out legitimate users after compromising a system

**Why Normal SSH Login Fails:**
```
1. SSH connects to server
2. Shell starts → .bashrc runs automatically
3. .bashrc executes exit command → prints "Byebye!"
4. Session terminates before you can do anything
```

**The Fix — SSH Command Execution:**
SSH has a built in feature to run a single command on a remote
server without starting a full interactive shell session:
```bash
ssh user@host -p port "command to run"
```
- The command in quotes is sent directly to the server
- It executes and returns the output to your terminal
- **.bashrc is bypassed** because no interactive shell is started
- Session closes automatically after the command finishes
```bash
ssh bandit18@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220 "cat ~/readme"
# SSH connects → runs cat ~/readme directly
# output (the password) is returned to your terminal
# session ends — .bashrc never gets a chance to run
```

**What I Learned:**
- `.bashrc` runs automatically on every interactive login — it can
  be weaponized to lock users out or run malicious commands
- SSH can execute commands directly without opening an interactive
  shell — very useful for automation and bypassing restrictions
- This technique is used constantly in real pentesting and
  system administration
- Non-interactive SSH sessions bypass `.bashrc` and `.bash_profile`

**Other Ways This Could Have Been Solved:**
```bash
# Use a different shell that doesn't read .bashrc
ssh bandit18@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220 -t /bin/sh

# Use SCP to copy the file instead of reading it
scp -P 2220 bandit18@bandit.labs.overthewire.org:~/readme ~/readme
```

**Key Takeaway:**
In real pentesting and forensics, startup files like `.bashrc`,
`.bash_profile`, and `.profile` are common places attackers hide
malicious commands — always check these files when investigating
a compromised system. Equally, knowing how to bypass them using
SSH command execution is an essential skill for working around
restricted or tampered environments.
